          <span class="essay-toggle-text">Chicken Spaghetti: A Mississippi Original?</span>
          <span class="essay-toggle-icon">▼</span>
        </button>
        <div class="essay-content" id="chicken-spaghetti-essay" hidden>
          <div class="essay-inner">
            <p>Craig Claiborne, the <em>New York Times</em> restaurant critic, lived in Indianola, Mississippi, in 1920s and 30s where his mother ran a boarding house and had a reputation as an excellent cook. In 1975, during an interview with WOR in New York, he was asked about his favorite childhood food. It was chicken spaghetti. The interview sparked interest in the curious "Mississippi" dish and a few weeks later Claiborne published his <a href="https://cooking.nytimes.com/recipes/1019165-my-mothers-chicken-spaghetti" target="_blank">family's recipe in the Times</a>. He claimed it was his mother's invention, and this variation probably was.</p>

            <p>Claiborne saw chicken spaghetti as a distinctly southern dish and Mississippians often view it as their own, but there is every reason to believe it first became popular in the Midwest and made its way down the Mississippi River to the Magnolia State sometime in the early 20th century. Although endless variations exist, it is rooted in both Italian cacciatore and Italian American tetrazzini. (I am planning a more extensive discussion of the historical roots of Chicken Spaghetti for a latter blog post, so we will leave it at that for now.)</p>

            <p>Recipes for chicken spaghetti evolved during the twentieth century, so dating the first appearance in a Mississippi community cookbook is tricky, but a pair of recipes from the mid-1920s are prime contenders. (See note.) In 1926 the Ladies Aid Society of the M. E. Church South of Augusta, Mississippi produced a cookbook to raise funds for "parsonage and church work." Two recipes for chicken spaghetti appear in the "Meats" section, and these relatively simple recipes are true to the churchwomen's promise that the cookbook would feature recipes that would "meet the wants of the average family." (4)</p>

            <p>The first recipe, a one-pot "Chicken with Spaghetti," was submitted by Mrs. J. D. Lugg. Cooks are asked to combine a package of spaghetti, flour, butter, pepper, a "small chicken boiled tender," and an egg, and boil the mix for an hour. (10) The second recipe was submitted by the committee that created the cookbook. Although the committee claimed that all the recipes in the cookbook were "tested and found satisfactory," one suspects that the committee had some doubts about Mrs. Lugg's one-pot recipe (as do I) and felt the need to include an alternative. The committee's recipe, "Chicken and Spaghetti," invites the homemaker to "prepare a chicken as for stew. Cook until tender. Add butter, salt, pepper and a package of spaghetti. Just before taking up[,] add a cup of cream and cover the top with a rich paste and boil a few minutes more. This is a good way to use the boney parts of a chicken." (13) (Okay, so this recipe is nearly as confounding as the first, but at least it includes some liquid to cook the spaghetti. The paste is never explained. Later recipes would reduce chicken broth and canned tomatoes to a paste, so perhaps this is reference to tomato paste.)</p>

            <p>Neither of the 1926 recipes would become iconic, and it is clear from the New Augusta cookbook's dueling recipes that Mississippians' ideas about chicken spaghetti were still developing. In fact, the cookbook committee included not only a chicken and spaghetti recipe, but a ham and spaghetti recipe as well, suggesting that even the chicken was still up for grabs. (The ham variation was a casserole, although that term was not used, that featured two layers of spaghetti covered with ground ham and cheese and topped with butter and a cup of sweet milk. (14))</p>

            <p>The earliest recipes featured variants of a white sauce, but some later versions featured both a white and a red sauce. The chicken spaghetti prepared by Craig Clairborne's mother blended a red tomato meat sauce with a white Béchamel sauce, but as the dish evolved, the white sauce often disappeared and was replaced by cheese (although, truth be told, endless variations continue to be made). The first of these tomato and cheese recipes to appear in a Mississippi community cookbook can be found in the "One Dish Meal" chapter of Tchula, Mississippi's <em>Our Favorite Recipes</em> created by the Parent Teachers Association in 1946. In this recipe (credited to Mrs. V. H. Gordin of Canton, Mississippi, a town fifty miles south of Tchula), a hen is covered in water and boiled "until ready to fall off the bone." The chicken is then removed from the stock and 3 cans of tomatoes, 2 onions, 2 bell peppers, 1 stack of celery, "1 button garlic," and three bay leaves are added. This mix is cooked "slowly, about five hours, until a 'well done' paste." The chicken is then cut up and added, the spaghetti cooked separately (ignoring the one-dish promise of the chapter) and then spaghetti and paste are placed in a casserole and covered with cheese (adding a third dish to this one-dish meal). Cooks are instructed to "bake until cheese is melted and spaghetti is hot." (89-90)</p>

            <p>As the dish became more popular, "Chicken Spaghetti" emerged as favored name for the dish and it was these simply titled dishes, regardless of the exact recipe, that we used to examine chicken spaghetti's rising popularity. Using a customized database of recipes extracted from over one hundred Mississippi community cookbooks digitized by University Libraries at Southern Miss, Suwan Aryal and I were able to trace the history of chicken spaghetti in Mississippi and compare its popularity to a venerable Southern favorite, fried chicken.<sup><a href="#footnote-1" id="ref-1" class="footnote-ref">1</a></sup> Although variations on chicken spaghetti were prepared prior to World War II, the dish gained its name and became a household favorite in the 1940s.</p>
      
      <div class="chart-container">
        <img src="/experimental-kitchen-visualizations/chicken-spaghetti-vs-fried-chicken.png" 
