            <p>Given that the first appearance of the dish with the title "Chicken Spaghetti" did not appear in our dataset of Mississippi community cookbook until 1946, chicken spaghetti's rapid rise is remarkable. It immediately surpassed the number of fried chicken recipes in the database. It was so popular that many postwar Mississippi community cookbooks included two or three recipes for the dish and at least one, <em>A Book of Favorite Recipes</em> published by the Warren County Home Demonstration Clubs in 1961, included four. In fact, its postwar popularity was so great that despite getting a late start, chicken spaghetti is the only entrée to appear in our list of the ten recipes most often included in Mississippi community cookbooks published from 1900 to 1970. All the other recipes were for desserts.</p>
      
      <div class="chart-container">
        <img src="/experimental-kitchen-visualizations/top_10_recipes.png" 
             alt="Top 10 Most Popular Recipes in Mississippi Community Cookbooks" 
             class="analysis-chart">

            </div>

            <p>Numerous factors contributed to chicken spaghetti's meteoric rise. Initially, at least, it parallelled Americans' embrace of pasta. Once viewed as a detested, even unsanitary immigrant food, macaroni benefited from the concerted efforts of American manufacturers and the U.S. government in the first third of the twentieth century to market it as a healthy, American product made from domestic Durum wheat. (<a href="https://scholarworks.wm.edu/items/0d9a2b0f-b327-435e-93ad-1d58b629ff00" target="_blank">Melissa Faith Gray</a>, 85-94) Grocery stores carried pasta packaged in sanitary boxes featuring recipes and pastoral scenes prior to World War I, and spaghetti and other macaroni dishes became increasingly popular in the decades that followed. (<a href="https://scholarworks.wm.edu/items/0d9a2b0f-b327-435e-93ad-1d58b629ff00" target="_blank">Gray</a>, 85-94; <a href="https://www.amazon.com/We-Are-What-Eat-Americans/dp/0674001907" target="_blank">Donna Gabaccia</a>, 68, 159) In Mississippi, spaghetti dishes moved from the vegetable section of community cookbooks in the 1920s to the entrée section (with meat sauce or meatballs) in the 1950s.</p>

            <p>Shortages and inflation during the Great Depression and World II probably fueled chicken spaghetti's popularity, although the relative dearth of community cookbooks published in Mississippi during the national crises makes this a little difficult to trace. However, domestic mass production of macaroni made it an inexpensive and filling staple in many homes, and, although meat was often scarce and expensive, chicken—still raised in the backyard in many rural areas and small towns—was, at least compared to other meats, available. (As Clairborne noted in his <a href="https://us.amazon.com/Craig-Claibornes-Feast-Made-Laughter/dp/0030640075" target="_blank">autobiography</a>, chickens were "depression food." (29))</p>

            <p>Chicken spaghetti was not only inexpensive and relatively easy to prepare, it also was appealing to young people, including the young Craig Claiborne. In the postwar baby boom, as women found themselves caring for more children (and, in many places in Mississippi, also working), simple and kid friendly foods like chicken spaghetti were popular. And unlike fried chicken, a tried-and-true favorite that every young woman would have learned to cook from her mother or Black servant, chicken spaghetti was new enough that people were eager to share their recipes.</p>

            <p>Chicken spaghetti's relative popularity compared to fried chicken also reflected the marginalization of southern cooking in Mississippi in the postwar years. Southern dishes remained popular, but in middle-class community cookbooks, the percentage of recipes that were Southern declined compared to non-Southern dishes. (This topic is explored more extensively in the larger book project.) Foreign, ethnic, and ethnically influenced dishes became increasingly popular in Mississippi as home cooks embraced national trends.</p>

            <p>Chicken spaghetti's rise, however, involved more than its low price, simple recipes, and kid fandom. The dish was not just beloved, but transformed into a native Mississippi dish, even though nothing about the dish is rooted in the state's culinary traditions. (Mississippi, for example, was not home to a significant number of Italian immigrants.) Many years ago, at a talk I gave at a public library on "ethnic American" food in Mississippi, one of the audience members approached me afterwards and told me she was a bit puzzled by my claims that Mississippians embraced ethnic cuisine because she never really thought of spaghetti as an Italian dish. Chicken spaghetti, it seems, had shed its ethnic origins. In a fascinating dissertation, <a href="https://scholarworks.wm.edu/items/0d9a2b0f-b327-435e-93ad-1d58b629ff00" target="_blank">Melissa Faith Gray</a> argues that the "confluent messages of government agencies, home economists, and business" in the 1920s, 30s, and 40s succeeded in marginalizing pasta's ethnic origins and promoting it as simply a healthy, adaptable staple, but advertisers reversed course in the post-World War II era and reintroduce it as an Italian food. (101) Chicken spaghetti, already emerging as a regional favorite, seems to have retained its local, non-ethnic identity.</p>

            <p>That transformation might help explain its popularity. As the dish was localized, it was also whitewashed. My forthcoming book explores the growing popularity of ethnic dishes in Mississippi and, in general, the Mississippi women who created community cookbooks were eager to embrace new, exotic ethnic recipes. This cosmopolitan attitude contributed to the success of other Italian dishes, from Italian spaghetti recipes to ravioli, but there was probably a ceiling that limited the success of these dishes. When "chicken spaghetti" became "Mississippi chicken spaghetti," its popularity soared. Meanwhile, fried chicken was suffering from the opposite problem. Following the war, Southern women claimed "southern cooking" as their own, ignoring and minimizing the role of Black cooks (an argument I explore more fully in the book, but that others, such as <a href="https://www.amazon.com/Cooking-Other-Womens-Kitchens-1865-1960/dp/1469606860" target="_blank">Rebecca Sharpless</a>, have written eloquently about). That whitewashing of Black food included fried chicken, but its long association with Black cooks and Black stereotypes may have made the associations with African American culinary traditions difficult to shake. Craig Claiborne's mother made chicken spaghetti her signature dish, but her Black cook, Blanche, prepare the fried chicken. (<a href="https://us.amazon.com/Craig-Claibornes-Feast-Made-Laughter/dp/0030640075" target="_blank">Craig Clairborne</a>, 29)</p>

            <p>In Mississippi, as the origins of chicken spaghetti blurred, it became a local dish popular at backyard barbeques and church picnics—and the most popular entrée in Mississippi community cookbooks published before 1970. For many, including <em> <a href="https://www.southernliving.com/recipes/chicken-spaghetti-casserole-recipe" target="_blank">Southern Living</a></em>, "Chicken spaghetti is a Mississippi original."</p>

